<showme.pack xmlns="Compositor"
             xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
             id="Exa_SequenceTypes"
             xsi:schemaLocation="Compositor &#xA;                    file:/C:/xampp/htdocs/moodle2.5/mod/msm/XSLTdocuments/Compositor.xsd">
	  <texsupport href="../Analysis_TeXSupport.xml"/>
	
	  <title>Types: Examples</title>
	  <showme>
		    <statement.showme>
			      <para>
            <para.body>For the sequence below decide if it is constant, bounded above / below, (strictly) increasing / decreasing, or alternating.</para.body>
         </para>
			      <math.display>
				        <latex>a_n := n</latex>
			      </math.display>
		    </statement.showme>
		    <answer.showme type="Solution">
         <answer.showme.block>
            <answer.showme.block.body>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <strong>Is the sequence constant?</strong>   We have <math>
                        <latex>a_0=0</latex>
                     </math>, <math>
                        <latex>a_1=1\neq 0</latex>
                     </math>, etc. Therefore it is not true that there is a number <math>
                        <latex>c</latex>
                     </math> with <math>
                        <latex>a_n=c</latex>
                     </math> for all <math>
                        <latex>n\in \NNr</latex>
                     </math>. – The sequence is not constant.</para.body>
               </para>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <strong>Is the sequence bounded below?</strong>   We have</para.body>
               </para>
			            <math.display>
				              <latex>a_n = n \geq 0</latex>
			            </math.display>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>for all <math>
                        <latex>n\in \NNr</latex>
                     </math>. Therefore the sequence is bounded below by any <math>
                        <latex>l\in \RNr</latex>
                     </math> with <math>
                        <latex>l\leq 0</latex>
                     </math>. – Note that supplying a lower bound for a sequence does not oblige us to find the best possible lower bound. All we need to supply is any number <math>
                        <latex>l</latex>
                     </math> with <math>
                        <latex>l\leq a_n</latex>
                     </math> for all <math>
                        <latex>n\in \NNr</latex>
                     </math>. Thus <math>
                        <latex>0</latex>
                     </math>, <math>
                        <latex>-\pi</latex>
                     </math>, <math>
                        <latex>-999</latex>
                     </math>, ... are examples of lower bounds for this sequence.</para.body>
               </para>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <strong>Is the sequence bounded above?</strong>   The answer is ‘no’ because every number in <math>
                        <latex>\NNr</latex>
                     </math> occurs as a sequence element, and <math>
                        <latex>\NNr</latex>
                     </math> is 
				<subordinate>
                        <hot>not bounded above</hot>
                        <crossref>
                           <theorem.ref theoremID="Thm_NNotBoundedAbove"/>
                           <info>
						
						                        <para>
                                 <para.body>Look up this fact</para.body>
                              </para>
					                      </info>
                        </crossref>
                     </subordinate>.</para.body>
               </para>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <strong>Is the sequence increasing?</strong>   For each <math>
                        <latex>n\in \NNr</latex>
                     </math> we have</para.body>
               </para>
			            <math.display>
				              <latex> 
					a_n = n &lt; n+1 = a_{n+1}
					</latex>
			            </math.display>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>Therefore the sequence is strictly increasing.</para.body>
               </para>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <strong>Is the sequence alternating?</strong>   For <math>
                        <latex>n\geq 1</latex>
                     </math>, we have <math>
                        <latex> a_n &gt; 0 </latex>
                     </math>. Therefore it is not true that two successive sequence elements have opposite signs. The sequence is not alternating.</para.body>
               </para>
		          </answer.showme.block.body>
         </answer.showme.block>
      </answer.showme>
	  </showme>
	
	
	
	  <showme>
		    <statement.showme>
			      <para>
            <para.body>For the sequence below decide if it is constant, bounded above / below, (strictly) increasing / decreasing, or alternating.</para.body>
         </para>
			      <math.display>
				        <latex>a_n := (-1)^n\cdot n^2</latex>
			      </math.display>
		    </statement.showme>
		    <answer.showme type="Solution">
         <answer.showme.block>
            <answer.showme.block.body>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <strong>Is the sequence constant?</strong>   The sequence is not constant because more than one number occurs as a sequence element; for example</para.body>
               </para>
			            <math.display>
				              <latex>a_5=-25 \neq 100 = a_{10}</latex>
			            </math.display>
			
			            <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <strong>Is the sequence bounded below?</strong>   We have</para.body>
               </para>
			            <math.display>
				              <latex> a_{2n+1} = -(2n+1)^2 &lt; -n </latex>
			            </math.display>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>for all <math>
                        <latex>n\in \NNr</latex>
                     </math>. We know that the set <math>
                        <latex>-\NNr</latex>
                     </math> is not bounded below. Therefore the given sequence is not bounded below.</para.body>
               </para>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <strong>Is the sequence bounded above?</strong>   The answer is ‘no’ because, for every <math>
                        <latex>n\in\NNr</latex>
                     </math>,</para.body>
               </para>
			            <math.display>
				              <latex>a_{2n} = 4n^2 \geq n</latex>
			            </math.display>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>and, we know that <math>
                        <latex>\NNr</latex>
                     </math> is
				<subordinate>
                        <hot>not bounded above</hot>
                        <crossref>
                           <theorem.ref theoremID="Thm_NNotBoundedAbove"/>
                           <info>
						
						                        <para>
                                 <para.body>Look up this fact</para.body>
                              </para>
					                      </info>
                        </crossref>
                     </subordinate>.</para.body>
               </para>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <strong>Is the sequence increasing?</strong>   For each <math>
                        <latex>n\in \NNr</latex>
                     </math> we have</para.body>
               </para>
			            <math.display>
				              <latex> 
					a_{2n} = n^2 &gt; -(2n+1)^2 = a_{n+1}
					</latex>
			            </math.display>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>Therefore the sequence is not increasing. With similar reasoning we see that <math>
                        <latex>a_n</latex>
                     </math> is not decreasing.</para.body>
               </para>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>
                     <strong>Is the sequence alternating?</strong>   For each <math>
                        <latex>n\in \NNr</latex>
                     </math> we have</para.body>
               </para>
			            <math.display>
				              <latex>\sign(a_n) = (-1)^n = - (-1)^{n+1} = -\sign(a_{n+1})</latex>
			            </math.display>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>Therefore this sequence is alternating.</para.body>
               </para>
		          </answer.showme.block.body>
         </answer.showme.block>
      </answer.showme>
	  </showme>
</showme.pack>
